The Use of Convolutional Neural Networks in Melanoma Detection¶

Kyla Perkinson, Spring 2023¶

Introduction¶

Motivation¶

Melanoma is the most common form of skin cancer for 25-29 year olds, and the second most common form of skin cancer for 15-19 year olds. Despite these alarming statistics, only about 16% of Americans between the ages of 18-29 years old visited a dermatologist in 2018. Even though melanoma is the deadliest form of skin cancer, the survival rate is 93% when it is detected in early stages.

Access to dermatologists is also a concern. Factors such as cost, hours of operation, and availability of appointments add to the lack of annual visits. A more accessible way for the general public to determine their risk for melanoma would significantly improve the chances of it being caught in earlier stages and thus increase survival rates.

In 2018, a study was done in which 58 dermatologists with varying backgrounds and expertise were measured on their sensitivity and specificity for melanoma classification. When using dermoscopy only, these dermatologists had an average sensitivity of 86.6% and specificity of 71.3%. In the scope of this study, the sensitivity is how many patients with melanoma were diagnosed with it, and specificity is how many patients that do not have melanoma were accurately given negative results.

With this project, I hope to demonstrate how a machine learning model, specifically a convolutional neural network, can be used in the detection of melanoma. Specifically, my goal is to develop a model that outperforms a sensitivity of 86.6% and specificity of 71.3%, as this would be an improvement from the dermatologists' diagnoses mentioned previously. I believe that machine learning models could someday be used not only in melanoma diagnosis, but the diagnosis of other cancers as well. This would provide the general public with an accessible resource in cancer detection.

Data Collection and Processing¶

The Dataset¶

The dataset that I will be using can be found here. This dataset contains 10,605 images of moles that are either malignant or benign. The dataset is split almost 50/50, with 5,500 benign images and 5,105 malignant images. Each image is 3x300x300 but will be resized to 1x96x96 to make training, validation, and testing faster. This downsampling will cause information loss, so with more time it would be beneficial to keep the images at the original size to prevent this loss of information.

Data Preprocessing¶

Each image will go through a number of transformations. This includes resizing the image to 3x96x96, center cropping it, grayscaling it, which results in resizing to 1x96x96, and normalizing the image to have a mean of 0 and standard deviation of 1. Normalization will make sure each feature has a similar range and thus improve the performance of the model.

The data will also be split into training, validation, and testing phases. I will be using about an 80/10/10 split, with 8,655 training images, 1,000 validation images, and 1,000 testing images. The validation and testing sets will be equally distributed between benign and malignant images, so 500 per class, while the training dataset will have slightly more benign images.

I am now going to define three hyperparameters for my model: batch size, learning rate, and the number of epochs. Batch size determines how many examples are sampled at once before updating the model's parameters. Learning rate is how much a model updates its parameters with respect to the loss gradient descent. A larger learning rate means the model would uppdate its parameters by larger values, however if the learning rate is too high it could hinder the model's performance by missing the minima and therefore not converging. A smaller learning rate means the model would update its parameters by smaller values, however if the learning rate is too small it could take too long to train the model. Lastly, the number of epochs is how many iterations the model trains on.

To start, I am going to use a batch size of 16, learning rate of 0.001, and number of epochs as 50. These will be updated if necessary.

def show(images, labels):
    fig, axs = plt.subplots(ncols=4, nrows=4, squeeze=False)
    for i in range(images.shape[0]):
        image = images[i]
        image = F.to_pil_image(image)
        axs[int(i / 4), i % 4].imshow(np.asarray(image), cmap='gray')
        axs[int(i / 4), i % 4].set(xticklabels=[], yticklabels=[], xticks=[], yticks=[])
        title = "Malignant"
        if labels[i].item() == 0:
            title = "Benign"
        axs[int(i / 4), i % 4].set_title(title, fontsize=8)

Building a Convolutional Neural Network¶

I will now begin developing the convolutional neural network. Convolutional neural networks typically have convolutional layers, pooling layers, and fully connected layers. Convolutional layers extract features from the input and pass them through an activation function, typically ReLU. Pooling layers reduce dimensionality by splitting up the feature map into patches and either keeping the maximum value from each patch (max pooling) or keeping the average value of the patch (average pooling). The output from the last max pooling layer is flattened and passed to fully connected layers. The output of the last fully connected layer is the input for sigmoid, which returns the probabilities for each class.

The architecture for the convolutional neural network I will be implementing includes two convolutional layers, each followed by ReLU and a max pooling layer, then two fully connected layers, with the first being followed by ReLU and the last being followed by sigmoid to output a value between 0 and 1. This output then predicts what class the image is. If the output is less than or equal to 0.5 the image will classified as benign, and if it is greater than 0.5 it will be classified as malignant.

In [ ]:
class CNN(nn.Module):
    def __init__(self):
        super(CNN, self).__init__()
        
        # defining convolutional layers
        self.conv1 = nn.Conv2d(in_channels=1, out_channels=16, kernel_size=3, stride=1, padding=1)
        self.conv2 = nn.Conv2d(in_channels=16, out_channels=32, kernel_size=3, stride=1, padding=1)
        
        # defining activation functions and max pool
        self.relu = nn.ReLU()
        self.sigmoid = nn.Sigmoid()
        self.maxpool = nn.MaxPool2d(2,2)
        
        # defining fully connected layers
        self.linear1 = nn.Linear(18432, 120)
        self.linear2 = nn.Linear(120, 1)
        
    def forward(self, x):
        x = self.conv1(x)
        x = self.relu(x)
        x = self.maxpool(x)

        x = self.conv2(x)
        x = self.relu(x)
        x = self.maxpool(x)

        x = torch.flatten(x, 1)

        x = self.linear1(x)
        x = self.relu(x)

        x = self.linear2(x)
        x = self.sigmoid(x)
        
        return x

Since I am going to be moving the model to the GPU, I also need to move my input to the GPU, which will be done during the training. In the code below, I am using .cuda() to move the model to the GPU.

Next I am defining the loss function and optimizer I will be using during training. Image classification problems most commonly use cross entropy loss, so I will be using the binary cross entropy loss function since I am working with two classes. I will also be using Adam as the optimizer, which updates the model's parameters based on a batch of training data instead of the entire dataset. This can also make the model converge faster and therefore decrease training time. I am choosing to use Adam because of its use of an adaptive learning rate. With standard stochastic gradient descent, a single learning rate is used throughout. With Adam, the learning rate is adapted based on gradients so that the model converges faster.

In [ ]:
loss_function = nn.BCELoss()
optim = torch.optim.Adam(model_original.parameters(), lr = learning_rate)

Now that the model, loss function, and optimizer are defined, I am going to be implementing the training and validation loops.

Training a neural network consists of forward and backward propogation. Weights and biases are defined for each layer. During forward propogation, the data is fed in batches through the network and the output for each layer is calculated by the weights and biases. After forward propogation, the loss function is used to calculate the error between the predicted and ground truth labels. Then, backward propogation computes the gradients of the loss function with respect to the weights and biases. The gradients are fed backwards through the network, updating the weights and biases at each layer based on the gradients and learning rate to minimize the error.

The validation data is then used to see how well the model can generalize what it learned during training to a new dataset. If the model performs significantly better on the training set than the validation set, it means the model is overfitting and learning the training set too well. This could be seen by high training accuracies but low validation accuracies, or low training loss but high validation loss. If the model performs poorly on both the training set and validation set, it means the model is underfitting and it has not learned enough patterns in the data to accurately classify the images. This could be characterized by low training and validation accuracies, or high training and validation losses. Ideally, I would like to see similar training and validation accuracies that are fairly high, with the losses for both sets decreasing significantly at first and eventually plateauing at a low value. This would indicate that the model is able to learn patterns in the data and generalize to new data.

In [ ]:
def train_model(model, num_epochs, train_dataloader, val_dataloader, optim, loss_function):
  mean_train_loss = []
  mean_val_loss = []
  mean_train_acc = []
  mean_val_acc = []

  for epoch in range(num_epochs):
      # training phase
      model.train()
      train_loss = []
      val_loss = []
      train_acc = 0.
      val_acc = 0.
    
      for idx, batch in enumerate(train_dataloader):
          images, labels = batch
        
          optim.zero_grad()
        
          # forward propagation
          outputs = model.forward(images.to("cuda"))
        
          # calculating loss
          loss = loss_function(outputs, labels.unsqueeze(1).float().to("cuda"))
        
          # backward propagation
          loss.backward()
        
          optim.step()
        
          train_loss.append(loss.cpu().detach().numpy())

          # determining how many images are correctly labeled by model
          for i in range(0, len(outputs)):
              output = outputs[i].item()
              label = labels[i].item()
              if round(output) == label:
                  train_acc += 1
    
      train_acc = train_acc / len(train_dataset)
      mean_train_acc.append(train_acc)
      mean_train_loss.append(np.mean(train_loss))
    
      # validation phase
      model.eval()
      for idx, batch in enumerate(val_dataloader):

          with torch.no_grad():
              images, labels = batch
              outputs = model.forward(images.to("cuda"))
              loss = loss_function(outputs, labels.unsqueeze(1).float().to("cuda"))
              val_loss.append(loss.cpu().detach().numpy())
            
              # determining how many images are correctly labeled by model
              for i in range(0, len(outputs)):
                  output = outputs[i].item()
                  label = labels[i].item()
                  if round(output) == label:
                      val_acc += 1
    
      val_acc = val_acc / len(val_dataset)
      mean_val_acc.append(val_acc)
      mean_val_loss.append(np.mean(val_loss))
    
      if epoch % 5 == 0:
        print("Epoch : {}, Train loss: {}, Train acc: {}, Val loss: {}, Val acc: {}".format(epoch, np.mean(train_loss), train_acc, np.mean(val_loss), val_acc))

  return mean_train_loss, mean_val_loss, mean_train_acc, mean_val_acc

There are a few updates that can be made to help prevent overfitting, which will be explored in the next section.

Reducing Overfitting¶

Adding a Dropout Layer¶

The first adjustment I am going to make is adding a dropout layer to the model's architecture. Adding dropout to the architecture causes neurons to be randomly dropped between layers, so the neurons are not fed to the next layer. This prevents overfitting because it the model cannot rely too heavily on one feature for classification. I am going to be adding a dropout layer after the first fully connected layer with a value of p = 0.5, which means that each neuron has a 50% chance of dropping out.

In [ ]:
class CNN_with_Dropout(nn.Module):
    def __init__(self):
        super(CNN_with_Dropout, self).__init__()
        
        # defining convolutional layers
        self.conv1 = nn.Conv2d(in_channels=1, out_channels=16, kernel_size=3, stride=1, padding=1)
        self.conv2 = nn.Conv2d(in_channels=16, out_channels=32, kernel_size=3, stride=1, padding=1)
        
        # defining activation functions and max pool
        self.relu = nn.ReLU()
        self.sigmoid = nn.Sigmoid()
        self.maxpool = nn.MaxPool2d(2,2)

        # defining fully connected layers with dropout in between
        self.linear1 = nn.Linear(18432, 120)
        self.dropout = nn.Dropout(p=0.5)
        self.linear2 = nn.Linear(120, 1)
        
    def forward(self, x):
        x = self.conv1(x)
        x = self.relu(x)
        x = self.maxpool(x)

        x = self.conv2(x)
        x = self.relu(x)
        x = self.maxpool(x)

        x = torch.flatten(x, 1)

        x = self.linear1(x)
        x = self.relu(x)

        x = self.dropout(x)

        x = self.linear2(x)
        x = self.sigmoid(x)
        
        return x

Adding Weight Decay¶

Complexity could be a potential reason the model is overfitting. If the model is too complext, it can prevent it from generalizing well to new data. In order to penalize this complexity, I am going to add weight decay to the model. Weight decay prevents the weights of the model from getting too large, and thus preventing the model from getting too complex. Weight decay is a regularization technique and it is applied during back propagation when updating the model's weights. The values for weight decay range from 1e-5 to 1, so I am going to start with a weight decay of 1e-5 and increase until the model is no longer overfitting.

Testing the Model¶

It is now time to test the models. I am going to be evaluating each model based on accuracy, precision, sensitivity (recall), specificity, and F1 score. These metrics will be used to determine the best performing model. In the scope of this project, accuracy is the probability the model correctly diagnoses a patient with or without melanoma, precision is the probability a patient diagnosed with melanoma by the model truly has melanoma, sensitivity is the probability a patient with melanoma is diagnosed by the model, specificity is the probability a patient without melanoma will receive a negative diagnosis, and the F1 score combines the precision and recall scores. A confusion matrix is also being calculated for each model, which provides a visual representation of true positive, true negative, false positive, and false negative classifications for each model.

In [3]:
model_names = ['Original', 'Dropout', '1e-5 Weight Decay', '1e-4 Weight Decay', '1e-3 Weight Decay', '30 Epochs']
accuracies = []
precisions = []
recalls = []
specificities = []
f1_scores = []

I am defining my testing loop, which consists of forward propagation for each batch.

In [ ]:
def test_model(model, test_dataloader):
  predictions = []
  correct_labels = []
  test_acc = 0

  model.eval()
  for idx, batch in enumerate(test_dataloader):
    with torch.no_grad():
      images, labels = batch

      outputs = model.forward(images.to("cuda"))

      # determining how many images are correctly labeled by model
      for i in range(0, len(outputs)):
          output = round(outputs[i].item())
          predictions.append(output)
          label = labels[i].item()
          correct_labels.append(label)
          if output == label:
              test_acc += 1

  test_acc = test_acc / len(test_dataset)
  return test_acc, correct_labels, predictions

Further Steps and Future Work¶

Further Steps¶

This tutorial demonstrates the implementation of a model that can identify a malignant mole with an accuracy of approximately 90%. However, there exists room for improvements. Further steps could be taken to improve the model's accuracy, such as data augmentation and hyperparameter tuning, focusing on batch size, learning rate, dropout probability, and the optimizer. For this tuning, grid search could be used. Grid search manually searches through a set of given hyperparameter combinations to determine the subset that optimizes the model's performance. Additionally, using images of the original size (3x300x300) and adjusting the convolutional neural network architecture to reflect this vould increase the accuracy as well since there would be no information loss due to resizing.

Future Work¶

Detecting melanoma from input images of moles was the main goal of this tutorial. I hope to further extend this project to implement a model that is able to detect other forms of skin cancer, and even extend its application to cancer detection in a broader sense. During data preprocessing, I also noticed that the majority, if not all, of the images in the dataset are taken from white patients. The next step in improving this model would consist of finding a more diverse dataset to train with. It is crucial to develop machine learning models with datasets that are representative of the human population as a whole in order to reduce biases in these models.
